### What problem does this feature solve?
When developing a component library, you will encounter the need to register subComponents. For example, the component `List` needs to register subComponents such as `ListItem` and `ListItemBrief`. In Vue, it is often necessary to register the full `List` component:

```js
import { List, ListItem, ListItemBrief } from './components'

Vue.component(List.name, List)
Vue.component(ListItem.name, ListItem)
Vue.component(ListItemBrief.name, ListItemBrief)

// List: <List />
// ListItem: <ListItem />
// ListItemBrief: <ListItemBrief />
```

In React, just:

```js
import { List } from './components'

// List: <List />
// ListItem: <List.Item />
// ListItemBrief: <List.Item.Brief />
```

It seems that Vue's approach is a bit more complicated, so I think it is possible to consider supporting components to register their subComponents.

### What does the proposed API look like?
```js
// List.vue
import ListItem from './ListItem.vue'

export default {
  name: 'List',
  subComponents: {
    Item: ListItem
  }
}
```

```js
// ListItem.vue
import ListItemBrief from './ListItemBrief.vue'

export default {
  name: 'ListItem',
  subComponents: {
    Brief: ListItemBrief
  }
}
```

```js
// main.js
import { List } from './components'

Vue.component(List.name, List)

// or, App.vue
import { List } from './components'

export default {
  name: 'App',
  components: {
    [List.name]: List
  }
}
```

This will register `${List.name}`, `${List.name}Item`, `${List.name}ItemBrief` once.

